      "question": "If $\\sin(A - B) = \\frac{1}{2}$ and $\\cos(A + B) = \\frac{1}{2}$, where $0^\\circ < A + B \\le 90^\\circ$ and $A > B$, find $A$ and $B$.",
      "answer": "$A = 45^\\circ, B = 15^\\circ$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the inverse trigonometric values to set up a system of linear equations.",
          "Solve the equations for $A$ and $B$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$A-B = 30^\\circ$ and $A+B = 60^\\circ. (A-B) + (A+B) = 30^\\circ + 60^\\circ \\implies 2A = 90^\\circ \\implies A = 45^\\circ. B = 60^\\circ - 45^\\circ = 15^\\circ$"
      },
